WEBVTT

00:02.882 --> 00:06.407
Grace, mercy, and peace be unto you from our Lord and Savior, Jesus Christ.

00:06.628 --> 00:09.732
Again, a portion of the Old Testament reading from the book of Isaiah.

00:10.954 --> 00:13.578
Strengthen the weak hands and make firm the feeble knees.

00:14.159 --> 00:18.305
Say to those who have an anxious heart, be strong, fear not.

00:19.467 --> 00:23.593
Behold, your God will come with vengeance and with recompense of God.

00:24.474 --> 00:26.457
He will come and save you.

00:27.859 --> 00:28.801
You'll join me in a word of prayer.

00:30.624 --> 00:32.306
O God, Heavenly Father, as we gather,

00:32.386 --> 00:33.147
on this day.

00:33.167 --> 00:46.089
As we journey through this season of Advent, today we ask that you would lead us to find joy in these promises that you have given to us, the joy of the coming of your Savior, and the joy of His future return.

00:47.612 --> 00:58.610
Now as we wait in this life and in this world, O Lord, for your promises to be fulfilled, as we wait and look forward, we ask that you would teach us to wait patiently and to wait faithfully.

00:59.810 --> 01:07.000
Lead us to do this today and throughout the season of Advent as we look to the birth of your son Jesus Christ and the celebration that comes with it.

01:07.020 --> 01:08.742
We pray in Jesus' name.

01:08.762 --> 01:09.042
Amen.

01:09.703 --> 01:10.745
The congregation may be seated.

01:10.785 --> 01:26.586
During the season of Advent, I like to work in somewhere during the season, one of these weeks, the topic of waiting well.

01:27.728 --> 01:29.490
It's really what the season of Advent is.

01:29.666 --> 01:33.150
historically meant to be and meant to do for us to teach us.

01:34.252 --> 01:45.285
Historically, Advent was a solemn, penitential season of fasting for early Christians, preparing for both Christ's first coming, his nativity, and for his second coming, the perusea.

01:45.926 --> 01:51.693
A dual focus that emphasized hopeful watching, waiting for the Messiah's arrival and the end times.

01:52.414 --> 01:59.282
Christians have been following this pattern of waiting through the season of Advent since about the fourth century.

01:59.618 --> 02:00.079
AD.

02:01.820 --> 02:06.906
So question that follows, how are we doing at the waiting?

02:06.946 --> 02:17.017
How are we doing at the slowing down during the season or even the fasting of this season if that's what it was meant to be?

02:18.819 --> 02:24.105
And the answer, of course, is that we live in a world that makes these practices quite difficult.

02:25.666 --> 02:29.010
Not only is this season one of the busiest of the year,

02:29.602 --> 02:32.565
But it seems like everything is constantly speeding up.

02:32.886 --> 02:35.909
We have constant distractions if we're not careful.

02:36.970 --> 02:49.824
And these constant needs that take us away from what we are called to focus on this season, responsibilities of this life, things to do, places to be, all of the stuff to get ready for this season.

02:49.864 --> 02:58.994
And yet it's meant to be a season of waiting, of patience, of hopeful looking and watching.

02:59.682 --> 03:11.338
As I hope this morning that we might be reminded of this, as we look to the people of the Old Testament here in Isaiah's day, they also, like us, were called to wait and to look and to watch.

03:12.600 --> 03:26.258
They were waiting for these promises which we find here given in Isaiah chapter 34, chapter 35, that one day the eyes of the blind would be opened, the ears of the deaf unstopped, the lame man leap like a deer in the tongue of the mute sing for joy.

03:27.202 --> 03:32.528
and waters breaking forth in the wilderness and streams in the desert.

03:33.710 --> 03:50.770
Essentially what's promised here is that all of the needs, all of the wants, the hopes of this world would be met someday, that this promise would come, that these promises would be kept and would be met, and the people looked and waited and longed for it, and in this way we have much in common with them.

03:51.618 --> 03:58.970
While we can look back and see the Messiah who has come, Jesus Christ our Lord, we still wait for the fulfillment of these promises.

03:59.010 --> 04:05.661
Our world is not the world that is promised in Isaiah chapter 35.

04:07.664 --> 04:18.642
We still deal with all these needs, all of these hopes that one day there would be perfect justice that the law would go forth and be followed

04:19.106 --> 04:37.254
that those needs that people have in this earthly life would be met, that those who are dealing with infirmities of various kinds, that blindness would be healed, deafness would be opened, all these promises that are given here, and we too are called to watch and to wait.

04:38.315 --> 04:48.050
And today, if possible, I would say we can even wait with joy if we really tap into this, if we really look for the fulfillment of this promise in our lives,

04:48.578 --> 04:52.064
That's where it may lead if we can find it.

04:53.447 --> 04:55.390
So that's what I will offer this morning.

04:57.274 --> 04:59.017
A couple of thoughts on this topic.

05:00.760 --> 05:03.585
I grew up in the age of dial-up modems.

05:05.408 --> 05:08.033
I imagine a number of you can remember this as well, of course.

05:09.456 --> 05:10.738
This was my first

05:11.522 --> 05:15.248
insight into what the internet was like was these dial-up modems.

05:15.348 --> 05:38.706
My dad was a fairly early adopter of technology and we had a computer at home and then I can remember when we had this little box that sat in the corner and plugged into the phone line and you would start it up and click a few buttons on the computer and then you would get all these beeps and boops and and you would be waiting for a while.

05:41.442 --> 05:47.434
And on the screen, a few words would flash as all of this noise was happening in the background, initializing.

05:47.454 --> 05:51.943
And then another one that I remember staring at quite a bit, please wait.

05:55.289 --> 05:56.131
You couldn't do anything else.

05:56.672 --> 06:03.986
And in fact, you shouldn't do anything else because if you started pressing buttons during that process, then things would actually

06:04.258 --> 06:12.247
get worse, you might slow it down, you might turn it off, you might interrupt what was happening, all those magical noises that were somehow connecting you to some other place in the world.

06:12.728 --> 06:15.911
And that was the promise of the early internet days.

06:15.971 --> 06:23.440
You could plug in this device, you could turn on your computer, and somehow you could be plugged into everything it felt like.

06:23.760 --> 06:25.983
And today, that's even more true.

06:28.345 --> 06:32.530
But you also, in the early days of computer, couldn't help but spend a fair amount of time waiting.

06:32.962 --> 06:40.854
And not just with the modem, but anytime an update had to be installed or even just starting up your computer sometimes would take three or four minutes for everything to get ready.

06:41.394 --> 06:44.719
So you had to spend time in this period of waiting.

06:44.840 --> 06:45.461
Please wait.

06:45.721 --> 06:51.249
And in fact, don't do anything because if you do something, if you take any other actions, you may break it.

06:51.570 --> 06:52.611
You may cause problems.

06:52.651 --> 06:54.754
You may interrupt what's already started.

06:57.578 --> 07:02.706
It's what this season is meant to be for Christians as well.

07:03.138 --> 07:09.066
We tap into, we have insight into God's promises, God's Word, all of Scripture.

07:09.106 --> 07:18.820
And the Bible even talks about this as being so valuable, the gospel, that we are given that angels long to look into it, to know the fullness of the gospel.

07:19.821 --> 07:31.858
And then you have pictures of the time of revelation where the people are gathered, the tribes and the nations are gathered around the throne and they're singing and they're worshiping around the throne of the Lamb, and they never seem to grow tired of it.

07:32.898 --> 07:35.180
They're longing for it, looking for it.

07:35.961 --> 07:42.387
They're always, unendingly rejoicing in the good news of God, of our Lord Jesus Christ.

07:44.169 --> 07:45.791
This is what we get to tap into.

07:46.872 --> 07:50.055
And I know, I've talked to enough people here that you feel it as well.

07:50.115 --> 08:01.106
Every now and then, sometimes in our worship services, as we sing, as we come into this place, as we come forward for communion, we get a sense of this reality.

08:01.442 --> 08:03.624
that heaven is here on earth even now.

08:05.146 --> 08:17.219
And yet, as we walk out the doors, maybe if we're done with the devotion in the morning and we turn to the rest of the needs of the day in our regular lives, we go out from these promises.

08:17.880 --> 08:30.994
We're waiting on these promises to be finally completely real and full and known to us all the time, because we go into the world and we're constantly met by other distractions and problems.

08:31.490 --> 08:42.186
things that need to be dealt with and illnesses and people in the hospital that we're praying for and just the ongoing trials of a broken world.

08:44.209 --> 08:46.292
So this is what we are called to do during this season.

08:47.413 --> 08:48.034
Please wait.

08:49.476 --> 08:58.690
We tap into and we can see and we have in front of us beautiful promises that we need to come back to over and over and over again and yet we know we are waiting for a world that is yet to come.

08:59.852 --> 09:01.394
But if we try to do too much,

09:02.434 --> 09:10.127
If we work too hard, if we go the wrong directions or look for the wrong sort of hope, then we can sort of mess that up.

09:10.167 --> 09:12.931
We can cause problems in our lives.

09:14.434 --> 09:15.596
That brings me to my second point.

09:15.616 --> 09:16.758
The first one, please wait.

09:16.798 --> 09:20.043
Number two, impatience.

09:20.063 --> 09:23.529
And something maybe we don't think about all that often.

09:23.609 --> 09:26.213
Impatience can be a sin.

09:26.254 --> 09:28.978
Impatience can be a sin.

09:31.010 --> 09:43.210
Because the sin is anything that we do that breaks God's law first or breaks God's commands, but anything that we do that brings harm to ourselves or harm to our neighbor, those around us.

09:43.430 --> 09:58.354
Anything that we do that breaks God's commands, there's the horizontal between us and God, but also anything that we do that brings harm to us and our ability to walk in God's light and the joy that God has given us or anything that we do that breaks our relationship with our neighbor.

09:58.786 --> 09:59.828
These are simple things.

09:59.968 --> 10:01.630
Impatients, can it be a sin?

10:02.752 --> 10:04.615
Well, what does impatience often lead to?

10:06.418 --> 10:06.658
Anger?

10:06.678 --> 10:09.723
Or being short with one another?

10:09.743 --> 10:21.241
Being filled with some sort of a desire to move on, and so this comes, and we can lash out against those around us.

10:21.501 --> 10:27.250
I heard a pastor say one time in a sermon, I don't think that this will probably happen, but I wish

10:27.394 --> 10:31.319
that when we got to heaven and we were waiting there, you can imagine, waiting outside the gates and they're St. Peter.

10:31.379 --> 10:53.746
And the thing that we had to watch before we could go in was the way we always treated people in passing, the way we always treated people that we didn't have a deep relationship, the way we always treated people that were in the service industry, especially when we were impatient, all the times that we had done this, that we had grown short and we had snapped at others.

10:54.114 --> 10:57.159
that we had treated someone unfairly that they did not deserve.

10:58.440 --> 11:18.130
He was imagining we should have to realize the way that we treat others, especially the people that we might consider as the people that are just there to serve us or to do something for us or to take care of us or to meet our needs and how quickly do we become impatient.

11:19.426 --> 11:30.059
Impatients can be a sin, and especially if it is directed towards God, it can overwhelm our lives because certainly there have been those who have grown tired of waiting on God and said, God, where are you?

11:30.119 --> 11:30.860
Are you really there?

11:30.880 --> 11:31.781
Are you really working?

11:31.821 --> 11:32.742
Are you still active?

11:32.802 --> 11:35.065
Are you really still meeting the needs of this world?

11:35.125 --> 11:36.847
Are you still answering prayers?

11:38.950 --> 11:45.938
And there's where impatience can grow and confess to and can become

11:46.114 --> 11:54.222
just grow out over all of us and all of our thoughts and all that we do and all of our responses to God and can even lead us away from God Himself.

11:54.983 --> 11:58.747
So in patience, yes, I think can be a sin.

11:59.948 --> 12:13.842
We are invited during the season to step back from all of that and to be reminded to wait, to wait patiently, to see God's faithfulness to us, to remember the God who has been forever patient with us as His people.

12:14.658 --> 12:30.623
despite the fact that we are impatient, despite the fact that we do turn away from him, that we grow tired of his promises, that we don't always come back to him as we should, that we run from God and to our own sins, our own desires, our own will, and yet in the face of all of this, what has God always done?

12:30.643 --> 12:37.374
He has been patient and faithful to us as his people.

12:38.456 --> 12:42.322
So impatience can be a sin and that can be a reminder for us the season of how we

12:42.850 --> 12:57.825
allow this to fill our lives, the ways that we're constantly going and becoming overwhelmed by what could be the stress of this life and how that can cause us to lash out against one another and even our God.

12:59.426 --> 13:01.428
Finally, number three, pulling on the leash.

13:04.511 --> 13:07.675
When I was in high school, my grandmother had a palmaranian dog.

13:09.316 --> 13:11.218
And I didn't like this dog very much.

13:12.610 --> 13:16.295
It was one of these small dogs, a little furball, that yipped and yapped.

13:17.937 --> 13:19.759
And it was always anxious.

13:21.542 --> 13:24.365
And so my grandmother, I would go out with her sometimes, so I would visit her.

13:24.706 --> 13:29.372
She lived down the hill from the school, the high school I attended, so I would walk down to her house sometimes after school.

13:30.093 --> 13:32.055
And I would go out with her on walks with this little dog.

13:32.095 --> 13:37.622
And the Pomeranian was always named Misty, perfect name for a little Pomeranian.

13:38.724 --> 13:40.466
It was always pulling at the leash.

13:41.794 --> 14:00.319
I can remember watching this and it drove me nuts because it would pull on the leash and then my grandmother would pull back on it and she was getting to the point where having a dog pulling on her was not always a good thing but it was constantly pulling on the leash, constantly going, constantly this little ball of anxiety and stress and pulling and pulling to the point that it was choking itself on the leash.

14:01.741 --> 14:08.530
No matter what we would do or try and I would take it and I would try to pull it back and get it to walk next to me and nothing would work.

14:08.550 --> 14:11.154
Always pulling at the leash.

14:11.330 --> 14:17.318
to the point that the dog didn't even seem to enjoy the walks because it was so stressed and anxious about just going.

14:17.378 --> 14:19.742
And of course, the reality is it didn't matter.

14:20.963 --> 14:24.949
And pull and pull and pull all you want, and the walk's gonna be the same length.

14:25.690 --> 14:28.634
You're gonna go the same places, you're gonna get to see the same things.

14:30.016 --> 14:35.523
And it just always drove me crazy that it was constantly pulling on the leash.

14:35.543 --> 14:40.530
Of course, thinking about impatience, thinking about ourselves, thinking about the season maybe,

14:41.762 --> 14:48.833
thinking about the ways that we allow stress and anxiety to come into our own lives.

14:49.234 --> 14:52.679
And we two do the same thing, I think, pulling on the leash.

14:53.340 --> 14:58.028
And I will admit that I struggle with this as well.

14:59.089 --> 15:03.276
And it doesn't help that we have, we don't have to be patient anymore sometimes.

15:03.296 --> 15:09.746
We don't really have to wait anymore because anytime we're even standing in line at the grocery store, we can pull a phone out of our pocket and there we've got entertainment.

15:11.778 --> 15:16.202
But how often are we waiting for the next thing and the next thing and the next thing?

15:16.262 --> 15:24.911
How often are we just struggling with stress and anxiety that's self-imposed, a leash that's invisible, but we have created it?

15:26.312 --> 15:31.797
And all of this is opposed to what God invites us to, especially during the season, but our whole lives as God's people.

15:32.618 --> 15:40.626
Our whole journey as being Christians, as being followers of Jesus Christ is meant to be one not of constantly pulling on the leash.

15:41.570 --> 15:49.900
but of walking with him, of being steadfast, of faithfully living into those things that he has called us to do in this life.

15:51.222 --> 15:52.263
And I'll close with this thought.

15:54.245 --> 15:56.868
We need to look and watch Jesus.

15:57.389 --> 15:58.691
Of course, we always do.

15:58.731 --> 16:01.534
But we need to look and watch Jesus.

16:01.614 --> 16:03.136
Watch Jesus through the gospels.

16:04.157 --> 16:08.242
You will never find one time that he is in a hurry.

16:10.370 --> 16:12.833
You'll never find one time that Jesus is in a hurry.

16:14.194 --> 16:18.239
Not even when his friend Lazarus is being placed in the tomb.

16:20.301 --> 16:26.928
In Luke chapter nine, verse 51, Jesus says, it says, he set his eyes towards Jerusalem.

16:27.809 --> 16:32.154
But then you get 10 more chapters before he gets there.

16:32.955 --> 16:36.178
And it's roughly six, seven months of time that has passed.

16:36.802 --> 16:38.144
He set his eyes towards Jerusalem.

16:38.444 --> 16:40.808
We know the important work that he's going to do there.

16:41.749 --> 16:49.621
The Savior of the world, going to be placed on the cross, going to go into the tomb, going to rise again on the third day for the salvation of the world.

16:52.165 --> 16:53.187
And yet he's not in a hurry.

16:55.610 --> 16:57.493
He's patient.

16:57.513 --> 16:59.777
He's kind to those who come.

16:59.977 --> 17:05.906
All of the multitude of the crowds who come and tug on his cloak and ask for his help.

17:06.338 --> 17:08.080
and have the needs of this world.

17:09.942 --> 17:10.723
And he's not in a hurry.

17:10.743 --> 17:11.364
He's patient.

17:11.845 --> 17:12.966
He's loving and kind.

17:14.628 --> 17:16.811
He lifts them up out of the darkness of their life.

17:16.851 --> 17:18.974
He offers healing to those who are sick.

17:19.494 --> 17:21.577
He brings food to those who are hungry.

17:21.617 --> 17:24.661
And he speaks of his father's kingdom.

17:26.923 --> 17:31.869
Not only does he do those things, but he spends much time in prayer.

17:34.132 --> 17:35.634
These are the things that we miss.

17:36.354 --> 17:37.956
when we are impatient with God.

17:39.097 --> 17:49.569
These are the things that we miss when we grow too weary or stressed or anxious about the next thing and the next thing and the next thing and we don't spend time where we are.

17:50.530 --> 17:58.399
The invitation of this season is to live into the good works that God has appointed us to do now, today.

17:58.459 --> 18:02.964
And sometimes that looks like sitting in the morning for 15 minutes in a devotion or in God's word.

18:03.285 --> 18:04.626
Sometimes that looks like sitting with

18:04.802 --> 18:08.786
a child for a half an hour or an hour and singing or reading a story.

18:08.826 --> 18:15.293
Sometimes that looks like going and meeting the need of someone in the world around us because this is what Jesus did.

18:16.454 --> 18:17.936
And we are invited to do that as well.

18:19.658 --> 18:26.625
So as we go through this season for the remainder of it, for what we have left of this advent, let us look to Jesus and walk with him.

18:27.767 --> 18:31.911
The one who was never in a hurry, though he came to bring the salvation of the entire world.

18:33.273 --> 18:34.674
So let us faithfully wait.

18:35.426 --> 18:40.859
and walk and see what God invites us to do as His people this season.

18:41.901 --> 18:43.144
In Jesus' name, amen.

18:45.951 --> 18:47.575
I invite the congregation to stand at this time.

18:47.615 --> 18:50.642
We continue with the offer to him, create in me.

